<pre class="lineno">  1</pre><pre class="inputline">Let's talk about Normal mode.</pre>
<pre class="lineno">  2</pre><pre class="inputline"> </pre>
<pre class="lineno">  3</pre><pre class="inputline">Yes, you can move with the arrow keys, but you should avoid using this crutch if</pre>
<pre class="lineno">  4</pre><pre class="inputline">at all possible (and it's possible).  I call it a crutch because real Vim users</pre>
<pre class="lineno">  5</pre><pre class="inputline">scoff at arrow key navigation with a certain sense of elitism.  Alas, to join</pre>
<pre class="lineno">  6</pre><pre class="inputline">the cool kids you need something different.  In Vim, these keys are "h", "j",</pre>
<pre class="lineno">  7</pre><pre class="inputline">"k", and "l", and these are the directions they move the cursor:</pre>
<pre class="lineno">  8</pre><pre class="inputline"> </pre>
<pre class="lineno">  9</pre><pre class="inputline">                      "k"</pre>
<pre class="lineno"> 10</pre><pre class="inputline">                      ---</pre>
<pre class="lineno"> 11</pre><pre class="inputline">                       |               You can either press them repeatedly or</pre>
<pre class="lineno"> 12</pre><pre class="inputline">                       |               simply press and hold.  For example,</pre>
<pre class="lineno"> 13</pre><pre class="inputline">            "h"  |-----+-----|  "l"    press and hold "j" until you see some</pre>
<pre class="lineno"> 14</pre><pre class="inputline">                       |               more text (there are 44 lines in total</pre>
<pre class="lineno"> 15</pre><pre class="inputline">                       |               the screen just shows the first 20).</pre>
<pre class="lineno"> 16</pre><pre class="inputline">                      ---</pre>
<pre class="lineno"> 17</pre><pre class="inputline"> </pre>
<pre class="lineno"> 18</pre><pre class="inputline">                      "j"</pre>
<pre class="lineno"> 19</pre><pre class="inputline"> </pre>
<pre class="lineno"> 20</pre><pre class="inputline"> </pre>
<pre class="lineno"> 21</pre><pre class="inputline">Nice.  Notice how awesome it is that your fingers can stay on home row while</pre>
<pre class="lineno"> 22</pre><pre class="inputline">navigating around the document.  "j" and "k" are probably the ones you'll use</pre>
<pre class="lineno"> 23</pre><pre class="inputline">the most to begin with.  Isn't it convenient how they're right underneath your</pre>
<pre class="lineno"> 24</pre><pre class="inputline">index and middle finger?  And yet, as convenient as this is, it defies</pre>
<pre class="lineno"> 25</pre><pre class="inputline">conventions that have been cemented into our brains by almost every piece of</pre>
<pre class="lineno"> 26</pre><pre class="inputline">consumer software ever developed, and for good reason.  They're ARROWS, after</pre>
<pre class="lineno"> 27</pre><pre class="inputline">all; their purpose seems pretty clear.  Just give "hjkl" a shot for a while and</pre>
<pre class="lineno"> 28</pre><pre class="inputline">soon it'll be second nature.</pre>
<pre class="lineno"> 29</pre><pre class="inputline"> </pre>
<pre class="lineno"> 30</pre><pre class="inputline"> </pre>
<pre class="lineno"> 31</pre><pre class="inputline"> Key    Action      How you'll remember this</pre>
<pre class="lineno"> 32</pre><pre class="inputline"> ---    ------      ------------------------</pre>
<pre class="lineno"> 33</pre><pre class="inputline">   j    Move down   "j" looks like a hook that points downward at the end of a</pre>
<pre class="lineno"> 34</pre><pre class="inputline">                    fishing line.</pre>
<pre class="lineno"> 35</pre><pre class="inputline"> </pre>
<pre class="lineno"> 36</pre><pre class="inputline">   k    Move up     "k" stands for K2 -- the second-highest mountain in the</pre>
<pre class="lineno"> 37</pre><pre class="inputline">                    world that for obvious reasons should remind you of things</pre>
<pre class="lineno"> 38</pre><pre class="inputline">                    that go up.</pre>
<pre class="lineno"> 39</pre><pre class="inputline"> </pre>
<pre class="lineno"> 40</pre><pre class="inputline">   h    Move left   It's to the left of "jk", your two most oft-used keys.</pre>
<pre class="lineno"> 41</pre><pre class="inputline"> </pre>
<pre class="lineno"> 42</pre><pre class="inputline">   l    Move right  It's to the right of "jk", your two most oft-used keys.</pre>
<pre class="lineno"> 43</pre><pre class="inputline"> </pre>
<pre class="lineno"> 44</pre><pre class="inputline">Type ":o fourth.html" and hit ENTER.</pre>
